1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Bf4 c5 (3... Bf5 {This has been played recently by top
players. The idea is pretty logical. Black is developing the bishop outside of
the pawn chain. The drawback of this move is that White can quickly attack the
b7-pawn.} 4. c4 e6 5. Qb3 $1 dxc4 {I feel Black is almost forced to go for
this to justify the move Bf5} (5... Nc6 {This is a standard way to react after
Qb3. Black is ready to meet Qxb7 with Nb4. The drawback of this setup is that
the knight is not very well placed on "c6"} 6. Nbd2 Bb4 (6... Bd6 {This is
possible, but White is better after the simple:} 7. Bxd6 cxd6 8. cxd5 exd5 9.
e3 $14 {I can't see compensation for the ruined structure.}) 7. a3 dxc4 8. Qxc4
Bxd2+ 9. Bxd2 $14 {The knight is still misplaced on c6 and Black has no
compensation for the bishop pair.}) (5... b6 {Weakens the light squares a lot.}
6. e3 $14) (5... Qc8 {as a rule, defending the pawn doesn't promise Black
equality. White should continue developing his pieces naturally, then play Rc1
and put some pressure on the c-file.} 6. Nc3 c6 7. e3 Be7 8. Be2 O-O 9. O-O
Nbd7 10. h3 $14 {Followed by Rc1. Giving up the centre with dxc4 gives White a
small but long-lasting advantage}) 6. Qxb7 Be4 7. Qxc7 {White should accept
the challenge and win a second pawn. My analysis shows that with an accurate play
he can keep the advantage.} Bb4+ (7... Qxc7 8. Bxc7 Bb4+ 9. Kd1 {This is an
additional option for White if Black takes on c7 first}) 8. Nbd2 Qxc7 9. Bxc7
Ke7 (9... O-O {this looks a bit slow and White is just in time to coordinate
his pieces after:} 10. a3 c3 11. axb4 cxb2 12. Ra2 Rc8 13. Rxb2 Rxc7 14. Nxe4
Nxe4 15. e3 $14 {White keeps his extra pawn}) (9... Nbd7 {This move is
probably less accurate as the knight picks out its way too early. In many
lines, c6-square will be better than d7} 10. e3 Rc8 11. Bg3 Bd5 12. a3 Ba5 13.
Bd6 $1 {, preventing Black's castling, was an excellent way to justify White's
previous move. In case of} c3 14. bxc3 Bxc3 15. Rd1 Ne4 16. Bb4 a5 17. Bxc3
Rxc3 18. Nxe4 Bxe4 19. Nd2 {White consolidates his position keeping his extra
pawn.}) 10. e3 Rc8 11. Bg3 Bd5 12. Kd1 $1 $146 {An improvement over
Aroninan-Carlsen game} Nbd7 13. Bh4 Kf8 14. Rc1 c3 15. bxc3 Rxc3 16. Rxc3 Bxc3
17. Bg3 $1 Bxa2 18. Ba6 $1 {with the idea to go Ke2 and bring the rook into
the game. White is slightly better here.}) 4. e3 e6 (4... Qb6 {Black can try
to benefit from the move order with quick c5 and attack the b2-pawn.} 5. c4 $1
{This is the best reply. White is abandoning the b2-pawn and developing the
initiative as quickly as possible.} cxd4 (5... e6 6. Nc3 Qxb2 7. Nb5 Ne4 (7...
Na6 8. Be2 Qb4+ 9. Nd2 Ne4 10. Rb1 Qxd2+ 11. Qxd2 Nxd2 12. Kxd2 {Believe it or
not comp thinks White is almost winning here with the threats like Nd6}) 8. Be2
Nc3 9. Nxc3 Qxc3+ 10. Nd2 Nc6 11. Rc1 Qa3 12. cxd5 exd5 13. O-O Be7 (13... c4
14. e4 $1) 14. dxc5 O-O 15. Nb1 Qa5 16. Nc3 $16) (5... Qxb2 {accepting the
sacrifice is quite risky} 6. Nbd2 e6 7. cxd5 exd5 (7... Nxd5 {this also failed
to equalize after:} 8. Rb1 {the pawn doesn't matter that much. White has a huge
lead in development} Qxa2 9. Bxb8 $1 {very common idea which is worth
remembering} Rxb8 10. Bb5+ Kd8 11. Bc4 Qa5 12. Bxd5 exd5 13. O-O $40 {Black's
position looks very difficult to play, his two extra pawns are not important
at all}) 8. Rb1 Qxa2 9. dxc5 Nc6 10. Bb5 Be7 {this modest move is Black's best
try} (10... Bxc5 {is well met by} 11. Be5 {[%cal Gb1a1]} Qa5 12. Bxf6 {ruining
Black's structure. Black king will not have any safe square on the board until
the end of the game.} gxf6 13. Qc2 Qb6 14. Ba4 Qa6 15. Qxc5 Qxa4 16. O-O $40 {
White has more than enough compensation for the sacrificing material}) 11. Ra1
Qb2 12. Qa4 O-O {Black manages to castle, but he has problems with the awkward
position of the queen} 13. O-O Bf5 14. Ra2 Qc3 15. Bxc6 bxc6 16. Nd4 Bd3 (16...
Bd7 17. Rc2 Qd3 18. N2f3 $1 $18 {[%cal Gf3e5]}) 17. Nxc6 Bxc5 18. Be5 d4 19.
Rfa1 Nd5 20. Nf3 $14 {We would round up the d4 pawn pretty soon. After that,
the a7 pawn will be weak and White's pieces are much more active.}) 6. Qxd4
Nbd7 (6... Qxd4 7. Nxd4 $1 {Thats the reason why Black should probably play
Nbd7 first so that White cannot take back with the knight.} a6 8. Nc3 dxc4 9.
Bxc4 Nbd7 10. Bg3 e6 11. O-O Be7 12. Be2 $14 {[%cal Ge2f3] This symmetrical
structure is quite unpleasant for Black. The bishop will land on the long
diagonal, the rooks will occupy c and d - files. Black will have a problem
developing his queenside.}) 7. Nc3 Qxd4 8. exd4 dxc4 9. Bxc4 Nb6 10. Bb5+ Bd7
11. Bxd7+ Kxd7 {Otherwise, Nb5 can be painful for Black.} 12. Bd2 $1 {
Sidestepping against Nd5 jumps} e6 13. Ne5+ Ke8 14. a4 a6 {Black can't allow
a5-a6} 15. a5 Nbd5 16. Ke2 Be7 17. Rhc1 $14 {The problem for Black will be his
kings' position as he can not castle anymore, our idea could be Ra4-c4 next}) 5.
c3 Bd6 {The only independent move, everything else will probably transpose
into the mainline} (5... Qb6 6. Qb3 c4 {Otherwise Qb6 doesn't really make
that much sense here} 7. Qc2 {Black can't play Bf5 and this setup doesn't make
any sense for him. White can choose between b2-b3 or e3-e4 breaks} Bd6 8. Bxd6
Qxd6 9. Nbd2 $14 {White is simply better here}) 6. Bd3 Bxf4 (6... O-O 7. Nbd2
Bxf4 (7... Nc6 8. Bg3 {Transposes}) (7... Qc7 8. Ne5 {is a transposition to
Chapter 3.}) (7... b6 $6 {is wrong here, because Black has no time for Bb7} 8.
Bxd6 Qxd6 9. e4 {A useful trick} Nxe4 10. Nxe4 dxe4 11. Bxe4 Nc6 12. dxc5 Qxc5
13. O-O Bb7 14. Qe2 Rfd8 15. a3 $14 {[%cal Gb2b4,Gc3c4]}) 8. exf4 {This is a
pawn structure that we are going to get on regular basis. White's doubled
pawns are not weak at all. White enjoys a space advantage on the kingside,
better central control and a semi-open e-file.} Qc7 9. g3 cxd4 10. Nxd4 {a thumb
rule here is that we always try to take with a piece on "d4". If White manages
to play Qe2 followed by Ndf3, his advantage will be undisputable due to the
control of the central squares d4 and e5.} e5 11. fxe5 Qxe5+ 12. Qe2 Qc7 13.
O-O Re8 14. Qd1 Nc6 15. N2f3 Bg4 16. Qc2 g6 17. Rfe1 {[%cal Gd3f1,Gf1g2]
Although the position is around even I prefer White due to the isolani on d5.})
(6... Nc6 7. Bg3 O-O 8. Nbd2 {Transposes}) (6... Qc7 {This just loses a move}
7. Bxd6 Qxd6 8. Ne5 $14 {[%cal Gf2f4,Gb1d2]}) 7. exf4 cxd4 8. Nxd4 Qc7 9. g3
O-O 10. O-O Nbd7 11. Re1 e5 12. fxe5 Nxe5 13. Qc2 $14 {[%cal Gb1d2] White is
slightly better, thanks to his better pawn structure.} *

