{[%evp 0,25,38,22,24,9,22,22,22,36,35,-21,29,23,32,46,28,2,28,28,30,27,27,15,
29,13,13,3]} 1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Bf4 c5 4. e3 Nc6 5. Nbd2 {The main
position of the enitre system. Now Black has few options at his disposal} Qb6 {
Probably the most critical line for Black in the entire setup.} (5... Bg4 {
this looks very logical. Black develops the bishop before playing e7-e6} 6. c3
e6 7. Qb3 Qc8 8. Nh4 {This is a common idea in such structures. White prepares
h3 and g4.} cxd4 9. exd4 Be7 (9... Qd7 {with the idea to go Bd6 in one go. It
looks logical, but Black loses valuable time.} 10. h3 Bh5 11. Bd3 Bd6 12. Bxd6
Qxd6 13. O-O (13. Qxb7 $6 {We shouldn't be greedy.} Rb8 14. Qa6 Rxb2 15. Bb5 $2
O-O 16. Qxc6 Qf4 {The point and Black is completely winning here} 17. Nhf3 Bxf3
18. Nxf3 Qe4+ 19. Kf1 Qc2 $19 {[%cal Gc2f2]}) 13... O-O 14. Rfe1 Rab8 15. a4 a6
16. Nhf3 {[%cal Ga4a5,Gf3e5] White is simply slightly better here.}) 10. h3 Bh5
11. g4 Bg6 12. Nxg6 hxg6 13. Be2 $40 {[%cal Ge1f1,Gf1g2,Gh3h4]}) (5... Nh5 {
This move has become very popular lately} 6. dxc5 $1 {White's most principled
reply.} Nxf4 7. exf4 g6 {This is a real pawn sacrifice. Black wants to prove
that his bishop pair fully compensates for the pawn's absence.} (7... Qa5 {
is another way of development, but White has a strong reply at his disposal.}
8. c4 $1 {Black loses some time for Qa5-c5 and White should open the game
immediately.} e6 9. a3 Qxc5 10. Bd3 Be7 11. O-O O-O 12. b4 Qd6 13. g3 $14) 8.
c3 Bg7 (8... Bh6 {This has been played by Grischuk a few times.} 9. g3 O-O 10.
Nb3 a5 11. a4 Bg4 12. h3 {This is an improvement over Grischuk game, I just
don't see any compensation for the pawn here for Black.}) 9. Bb5 O-O (9... Qc7
10. Nb3 a6 11. Be2 O-O (11... Qxf4 {Black can take the pawn, but White still
has an initiative after:} 12. Qxd5 Be6 13. Qd2 Qa4 14. O-O Bxb3 15. axb3 Qxb3
16. Qf4 $1 {[%cal Ge2c4] The material is equal, but White has several
dangerous threats.} O-O 17. Bc4 Qxb2 18. Rfc1 $40 {[%cal Ga1b1,Gf3g5]}) 12.
Qxd5 Rd8 13. Qe4 Bf5 14. Qa4 Bd7 15. Rd1 e5 {Black desperately tries to open
the position.} 16. Rd6 Bf8 17. Rd2 Bh6 18. Ng5 $1 exf4 19. Nf3 {I feel that
Black doesn't have enough compensation for the pawn.}) 10. Bxc6 bxc6 11. Qa4
Qc7 12. O-O f6 13. c4 Bh6 14. g3 e5 15. Rfe1 a5 16. cxd5 cxd5 17. Rac1 {
Once again, I don't feel Black has enough compensation for the pawn.}) (5...
cxd4 {Entering Caro-Kann structure} 6. exd4 Bf5 {Black avoids dc5 idea in this
setup} (6... Qb6 {the drawback of the early cxd4 is that White can play} 7. Nb3
Bg4 (7... Bf5 {Looks logical, but doesn't solve all the problems.} 8. a4 a6 9.
a5 {It is always useful to fix the queenside.} Qd8 10. Ne5 e6 11. Nxc6 bxc6 12.
Be2 {Black's a6-pawn is a long-term weakness} Be7 13. O-O O-O 14. c4 $14) 8. h3
Bh5 9. a4 a6 10. a5 Qd8 11. g4 Bg6 12. Ne5 $14 {White is more active and Kxc6
is a positional threat. The advanced h4-h5 is also in the air. I think that
Black will experience some problems here.}) 7. Bb5 e6 (7... Rc8 {abandonning
the development of the kingside for one move is a bit risky} 8. Ne5 Qb6 9.
Bxc6+ bxc6 10. Nb3 {g4 is a big threat now} h6 11. O-O e6 12. c4 Be7 13. c5 Qa6
14. h3 O-O 15. Re1 $14 {[%cal Ge1e3,Gb3c1]}) 8. Ne5 Qb6 (8... Rc8 $2 9. Nxc6
bxc6 10. Ba6 {wins an exchange.}) 9. c4 dxc4 10. Bxc6+ bxc6 11. Ndxc4 $14 {
White is slightly better thanks to the weak pawn on c6}) (5... Bf5 {this move
leaves the c5-pawn unprotected} 6. dxc5 $1 e6 7. b4 (7. Nd4 {White can return
the pawn in another way and get a slightly better position after} Bxc5 8. Nxf5
exf5 9. c3 $14 {White has slightly better position thanks to his bishop pair
and better pawn structure.}) 7... Nxb4 8. Bb5+ Nc6 9. Nd4 Qc8 10. N2b3 a6 11.
Ba4 Be7 12. O-O O-O 13. Nxc6 bxc6 14. Rc1 $14 {[%cal Gc2c4] White has a clear
plan and also an object to attack (c6-pawn). On the other hand, I can't see
how Black can use his pawn majority in the centre.}) 6. dxc5 Qxb2 $1 {Black
needs to accept the challenge. Now his structure is much better and if he
manages to finish the development, he will be better. The problem is that the
queen is always in trouble and White has a significant lead in development.
White has the c4 and e4 breaks to open the game in an appropriate moment.} (
6... Qxc5 $6 {This move is inaccurate and White quickly gets a slightly better
position after:} 7. a3 {With the idea to c4-b4 next.} g6 (7... Bg4 8. c4 e5 9.
Bg5 e4 10. b4 Qd6 11. h3 Bh5 12. g4 Bg6 13. Nh4 $14 {[%cal Gf1g2]}) (7... Bf5
8. c4 e6 9. b4 Qb6 10. c5 Qd8 11. Bb5 $16) (7... Nh5 {This just loses a pawn
after} 8. Nb3 Qb6 9. Qxd5 $16) 8. b4 Qb6 (8... Qc3 9. b5 Na5 10. Be5 Qc5 11.
Bd4 Qc7 12. c4 Nxc4 13. Nxc4 dxc4 14. Qa4 Bg7 15. Bxc4 O-O 16. O-O $16) 9. c4
Bg7 10. c5 Qd8 11. b5 Na5 12. Rc1 $14 {[%cal Gf1e2,Ge1g1]}) 7. Rb1 Qc3 (7...
Qxa2 $2 {taking the second pawn is just a mistake} 8. Bb5 $1 $40 {[%csl Ga2]
[%cal Gd2b3]}) (7... Qa3 {Thanks to the effort of Russian GM Sarana this move
has been getting popular recently.} 8. Bb5 g6 9. Ne5 Qxc5 10. c4 Bg7 11. Qa4
dxc4 12. Bxc4 a6 13. Nb3 $146 {here I suggest this interesting novelty which
leads to a quite sharp position after:} Qb6 (13... Qb4+ {is safer, but not
very ambitious} 14. Qxb4 Nxb4 15. Bxf7+ Kf8 16. Nc5 $14) 14. Bxf7+ Kf8 15. Nxc6
Bd7 (15... Qxc6 16. Qxc6 bxc6 17. Bc4 $14) 16. Be6 Bxc6 17. Qd4 Qxd4 18. Nxd4
Bxg2 19. Rg1 Be4 20. Rc1 $44 {After all the drama is over, I feel we have
enough compensation for the pawn.}) 8. Bb5 {Now Black has two main setups, one
with e6 and another one with g6} g6 (8... e6 9. O-O Be7 (9... Bxc5 {taking the
pawn with the bishop is not an option here. Black usually leaves this task to
the queen.} 10. Be5 Qa5 11. c4 $16 {[%cal Gd2b3]}) 10. e4 O-O (10... a6 {
was tried in a recent correspondence game, but White is much better after:} 11.
Bxc6+ bxc6 12. Ne5 Qxc5 (12... O-O 13. Nxc6 Qxc5 14. Nxe7+ Qxe7 15. e5 Nd7 16.
Qg4 $40 {[%cal Rb1b3,Rb3g3]}) 13. c4 Nxe4 14. Qh5 O-O 15. Nxe4 dxe4 16. Rb3 $16
{White's attack is devestating} f6 17. Rh3 fxe5 18. Be3 Qb4 19. Qxh7+ Kf7 20.
Rh6 Bf6 21. Qg6+ Ke7 22. Rh7 {1-0 (22) Wenzel,A (2214)-Hjorth,J (1877) ICCF
2021}) 11. e5 Nd7 12. Nb3 Qb4 13. Nfd4 Nxd4 14. Nxd4 Qxc5 15. Re1 {This is an
important position for Black if they want to go with e6 setup} a6 (15... Bd8
16. Re3 Qe7 17. Bxd7 Qxd7 18. Rg3 $40 {[%cal Gd1g4,Gf4h6]}) 16. Bd3 g6 17. Nb3
Qc7 18. Qg4 $44 {With the idea to go h4-h5 next and if Black himself plays h5
then we can switch to piece play with Bg5-Re3/g3}) (8... Qxc5 9. O-O $16 {
[%cal Gc2c4] with the idea to go c4 next, White's initiative is too powerful
for Black to handle.}) 9. e4 a6 (9... dxe4 {this is also possible, but opening
the game like that is not helping Black.} 10. Be5 Qa5 (10... Qxc5 $2 {This was
played by Ding but seemed to be a mistake.} 11. Bxf6 exf3 12. Bxh8 fxg2 13. Rg1
Bf5 14. Bd3 O-O-O 15. Rb5 Qd6 16. Rxf5 gxf5 17. Rxg2 {I don't see any
compensation for the piece}) 11. O-O $1 {This piece sacrifice is very
interesting. In my opinion, White has more than enough compensation for the
sacrificed material.} exf3 12. Bxc6+ bxc6 13. Qxf3 Nd5 14. Bxh8 Qxd2 15. c4 f6
16. Rfd1 Qf4 17. cxd5 Qxf3 18. gxf3 Bf5 19. Rb7 cxd5 20. c6 {All is pretty
much force until here. I think that Black still has to make a few more moves
precisely to equalize here completely.}) 10. Be5 Qxc5 11. Bd4 Qa3 12. Rb3 Qxa2
13. Bxc6+ bxc6 14. Qe2 Bg7 (14... Qxc2 $6 {is too greedy!} 15. O-O Bh6 (15...
Bg7 16. Ra1 $1 {[%cal Gb3b2]}) 16. Rb2 Qa4 17. Bxf6 exf6 18. exd5+ $18) 15. O-O
Qa5 16. exd5 (16. e5 {gives White nothing more than a draw} Ne4 17. Ra1 Qc7 18.
Bb6 Qb7 19. Ba5 Qa7 $11) 16... cxd5 17. Rb6 $1 {[%csl Rf6][%cal Gf1a1] Black's
queen is still in trouble} Nh5 18. Ne5 Qa4 19. Nc6 O-O 20. Ra1 (20. Nxe7+ {
looks interesting too} Kh8 21. Bxg7+ Nxg7 22. Qe5 Re8 23. Qf6 $13) 20... Qxd4
21. Nxd4 Bxd4 22. Rbb1 Bxa1 23. Rxa1 {Black has played at least ten only moves
and here is my conclusion. Maybe Black can make a draw here, but we can keep
on playing without any risk after all queen is a queen :)} *

