{[%evp 0,39,24,22,22,9,24,32,22,20,43,-19,12,4,5,9,4,13,19,15,20,-10,-10,-71,
-83,-83,-90,-94,-91,-73,-52,-52,-60,-54,-43,-43,-32,-34,5,-8,-20,-23]} 1. d4 d5
2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Bf4 c5 {This is the most frequent move order. Black immediately
strikes in the centre.} ({Another essential direction is} 3... e6 4. e3 Bd6 5.
Ne5 {I like this concept a lot. White saves a tempo on Bg3. After providing
the e5-knight with the necessary support, White will be ready to start a
kingside attack by advancing the h-pawn.} ({The problem with} 5. Bg3 {is that
after} O-O 6. Nbd2 c5 7. c3 Qc7 8. Bd3 Nbd7 {[%cal Ge6e5] Black wins the fight
for the e5-square. He can already consider playing ...e6-e5.}) 5... O-O 6. Nd2
c5 7. c3 Qc7 (7... Nc6 8. Bd3 Qc7 {transposes to 7...Qc7} (8... Ne7 9. h4 {
is another transposition.})) ({Another common move order is} 7... b6 {[%cal
Gc8a6] Black is planning to exchange the light-squared bishops via a6. In this
case, White's most precise reaction would be} 8. h4 {When our centre is not
under immediate pressure, we should always consider this idea.} Qc7 ({
Exchanging the light-squared bishops with} 8... Ba6 {is a time-consuming
operation. Meanwhile, White will start gaining space on the kingside. A
possible line would be} 9. Bxa6 Nxa6 10. h5 h6 11. Qe2 Nc7 12. g4 $40 {with
decent attacking chances on the kingside.}) 9. h5 Nbd7 ({Another illustrative
line would be} 9... Nc6 10. Nxc6 Bxf4 11. exf4 Qxc6 12. h6 g6 13. Qe2 $14 {
[%cal Ge2e5] White is clearly better. The h6-pawn is quite annoying both in
the middlegame and in the endgame.}) 10. Ndf3 {Having saved a tempo on Bg3,
White is in time to support his central knight.} cxd4 11. exd4 Ne4 12. Bd3 Nxe5
13. dxe5 $1 Bc5 14. O-O $16 {[%cal Ga1c1,Gc3c4] White is ready to follow with
Rc1 and c3-c4. The e4-knight is unstable.}) 8. Bd3 Nc6 (8... Nbd7 9. Ndf3 {
This position would be perfect for Black if White spent tempo for Bg3, but now
White can take the initiative.} Ne4 10. O-O b6 (10... f6 $6 {is well met by
the typical} 11. Nxd7 Bxd7 12. Bxe4 dxe4 13. Bxd6 Qxd6 14. dxc5 $14) 11. Re1 $1
{A clever little move asking Black to show his hand first A clever little move
asking Black to show his hand first} Bb7 12. Nxd7 Qxd7 13. Bxe4 dxe4 14. dxc5
exf3 15. Qxd6 Qb5 16. a4 Qxc5 17. Qxc5 bxc5 18. Bd6 {This endgame with
opposite-coloured bishops could be very unpleasant for Black. White's queenside
majority will start moving soon.} Rfc8 19. e4 fxg2 20. a5 a6 21. Kxg2 $14) 9.
Ndf3 Ne7 $1 {Here I would like to give you two suggestions} (9... Nd7 10. Ng5 $1 $16) (9... Ne4 10. O-O (10.
Qc2 cxd4 $1 {saves the day for Black} (10... f5 11.
Nxc6 Qxc6 12. O-O $14 {[%cal Gf3e5,Gf2f3]}) 11. Nxc6 dxe3 (11... bxc6 12. Bxd6
Qxd6 13. cxd4 Qb4+ 14. Nd2 Nxd2 15. Qxd2 Qxd2+ 16. Kxd2 $14) 12. Bxd6 exf2+ 13.
Ke2 Qxd6 14. Nce5 f6 15. Rhd1 fxe5 (15... Qe7 16. Ng4 f5 17. Nge5 $14) 16. Bxe4
Bd7 {Black has enough compensation here. Black has enough compensation here.})
(10. h4) 10... f6 11. Nxc6 Qxc6 12. Bxe4 dxe4 13. Bxd6 Qxd6 14. Nd2 $14) (9...
b6 10. Nxc6 $1 {In this move-order, we have this useful intermezzo In this
move-order we have this useful intermezzo} Qxc6 11. h4 a5 12. h5 h6 {Black
can't let White pawn reach on h6 You cant let White pawn reach on h6} (12...
Ba6 13. Bxa6 Rxa6 14. h6 g6 15. O-O $14) 13. Qe2 {with the Ba6 stopped we can
continue with Ne5 and g4. I feel White has a risk free attack here with the
Ba6 stopped we can continue with Ne5 and g4. I feel White has a risk free
attack here}) 10. Rc1 $146 {We want to make as many useful moves as we can
before deciding whether to go for h4 and attack on the kingside or to go 0-0
and play positionally We want to make as many useful moves as we can before
deciding whether to go for h4 and attack the kingside or to go 0-0 and play
positionally} (10. Ng5 $146 h6 11. h4 Bd7 (11... b6 12. Qc2 {[%cal Gd3h7]} Nf5
13. Qe2 $40 {[%cal Gg2g4]}) 12. Ngf3 Be8 13. dxc5 Qxc5 14. g4 Qc7 15. g5 Nh5
16. gxh6 f6 17. hxg7 Nxg7 18. Rg1 Bxe5 19. Nd4 Qd7 20. Qf3 Bxd4 21. exd4 $40 {
[%cal Ge1c1] Objectively, maybe Black can hold this but in a practical game, I
feel White would win 90 percent of the time here. Objectively maybe Black can
hold this but in a practical game I feel White would win 90 percent of the
time here.}) 10... b6 11. Ng5 h6 12. h4 {we didn't play Ng5 to go back} Bb7 (
12... Nf5 13. g4) 13. Nh3 {after we provoke h7-h6, we can move the knight back}
Ne4 14. Qg4 Nf6 15. Qe2 cxd4 (15... Ne4 $6 16. O-O Nc6 17. f3 Nf6 18. Ng4 $1
$14 {[%cal Ge3e4,Gf4d6]}) 16. exd4 Ne4 17. O-O (17. Qg4 $11 {This is just in
case you forget your prep and wants to chicken out and make a draw :)})
17... f6 18. c4 $1 {White should go for this force variation now} fxe5 19. cxd5
Nc5 20. dxe5 Rxf4 21. Nxf4 Bxe5 22. Nxe6 Qd6 23. Nxc5 bxc5 24. Rfe1 Bf6 25. Qe3
{[%csl Rc5] Once again objectively it is around equal but we don't risk
anything here. Once again objectively it's around equal but we don't risk
anything here.}) 4. e3 Nc6 5. Nbd2 {This is the most precise move order.} ({
I wouldn't suggest starting with} 5. c3 {in view of} Qb6 6. Qb3 c4 7. Qc2 Bf5 {
which is considered to be fine for Black.}) 5... e6 6. c3 {Here Black has at
least four decent possibilities.} Bd6 {This is by far the main line.} ({A
popular option is} 6... cxd4 7. exd4 Nh5 8. Be3 Bd6 {The idea of Black's setup
is to prepare an eventual central expansion by means of ...f7-f6 followed by ..
.e6-e5. White, however, has enough time to organize his forces by using the
vulnerable h5-knight.} 9. Ne5 g6 ({Worse is} 9... Nf6 $6 10. f4 O-O 11. Qf3 $40
{[%cal Gf1d3] with a dream position for White.}) 10. Nd3 Ng7 ({Similar is} 
10... O-O {when once again, White should play} 11. g3 {Remember this idea. By
developing the bishop to g2, White makes the idea ...f7-f6 followed by ...
e6-e5 is rather difficult.} b6 12. Bg2 Ba6 13. Nf3 f6 14. Bh6 Re8 15. O-O {
[%cal Gf1e1] Black can only activate himself by playing e5 but that would make
d5-pawn really weak, thus giving White a slight edge without any risk.}) 11. g3
O-O 12. Bg2 b6 ({The immediate} 12... Nf5 {is well met by} 13. Bf4 b6 14. Bxd6
Nxd6 15. Ne5 Bb7 16. O-O Qe7 17. Re1 $14 {with a stable advantage for White.})
13. Nf3 {I think it makes sense to start with this move order.} ({The
alternative is} 13. O-O Nf5 ({Less precise is} 13... Ba6 14. Nf3 $14 {[%cal
Gf1e1,Ge3f4] followed by Re1 and Bf4.}) 14. Re1 (14. Bf4 Ba6 {is the point of
Black's move order starting with 12...b6.}) 14... Nxe3 15. Rxe3 Ne7 16. Nf3 Nf5
17. Re1 Qc7 18. Nfe5 Bb7 19. Qd2 {The position is close to equal but I believe
White has a simple plan of advancing the h- pawn down the board whereas I don't
see any clear-cut plan for Black.}) 13... Nf5 ({Nothing gives} 13... f6 14. h4
Nf5 15. Bc1 $1 {[%cal Ge1g1] Black has no counterplay.}) 14. Bc1 Ba6 15. O-O
$14 {[%cal Gf1e1,Gh2h4]}) ({Another interesting option is} 6... Nh5 7. Bg5 f6 (
7... Qb6 $6 {is a bit inaccurate now as after} 8. dxc5 Bxc5 9. b4 {with the idea
to follow with e3-e4 next. If Black goes Be7 then we have b4-b5 there.}) 8. Bh4
g6 9. Be2 cxd4 ({Another idea is} 9... Ng7 {[%cal Gg7f5] Trying to obtain the
bishop pair by means of ...Nf5. This idea, however, is rather time-consuming.}
10. Bg3 Nf5 11. O-O cxd4 ({It's important that White can answer} 11... h5 {with
} 12. Nh4 $1) 12. cxd4 Nxg3 13. hxg3 Bd6 14. Bb5 $1 {[%cal Gb5c6]} Bd7 15. e4
$14) 10. cxd4 Be7 11. Rc1 O-O 12. Nb3 Ng7 13. O-O Nf5 14. Bg3 Qb6 15. a3 {
White's queenside pressure gives him a slight edge. He is ready to proceed
with Qc2 followed by Nc5.}) ({A bit passive is} 6... Be7 7. Ne5 ({But not} 7.
h3 Bd6 {which is the point of Black's play. Now White doesn't have Bg3.}) 7...
O-O ({Exchanging the e5-knight is always a risky decision. For example. after} 
7... Nxe5 8. dxe5 Nd7 9. h4 {The e5-pawn dramatically increases White's
kingside attacking chances.} f6 10. exf6 Nxf6 11. h5 O-O ({Stopping the
advance of the pawn with} 11... h6 {is well met by} 12. Qf3 O-O 13. Qg3 $40 {
when White's attack continues.}) 12. h6 g6 13. Nf3 {White is much better
thanks to the pawn on h6}) ({The attempt to simplify the position with} 7...
Nd7 8. Nxd7 Bxd7 {is again answered by the thematic} 9. h4 $1 cxd4 ({The
concrete play arising after} 9... Qb6 10. Rb1 cxd4 11. exd4 e5 {does not solve
the problems since} 12. dxe5 Bf5 13. Nf3 Bxb1 14. Qxb1 $44 {[%cal Gf1d3,Ge1g1]
gives White more than enough compensation for the exchange.}) 10. exd4 Bxh4 11.
Qh5 {White develops a dangerous initiative for only one pawn.} Be7 ({Another
possible line would be} 11... Bf6 12. O-O-O g6 (12... Qb6 13. Kb1) 13. Qh2 Qa5
14. Kb1 O-O-O 15. Rc1 $1 {[%cal Gd2b3,Ge1d3,Gc3c4] The Black king is in danger.
White is ready to continue with Nb3 followed by c3-c4.} g5 16. Qh6 $1) 12. Bd3
(12. O-O-O Qb6 13. Kb1 g6 14. Qh2 O-O-O 15. Rc1 g5 {Now White doesn't have the
Qh6 trick as the bishop is on e7.}) 12... Qb6 13. Rb1 g6 14. Qh6 O-O-O 15. b4
f6 16. O-O $44 {with sufficient compensation for the pawn.}) (7... Qb6 8. Rb1 {
Usually, when you can meet Qb6 with Rb1 it makes it less desirable for Black.})
8. Bd3 Nxe5 (8... Nd7 9. O-O Ndxe5 10. dxe5 f6 11. exf6 Bxf6 12. Bg3 $14 {
[%cal Ge3e4]}) 9. dxe5 Nd7 10. h4 f5 11. g4 {White's attacking potential looks
massive here.}) 7. Bg3 O-O 8. Bd3 b6 {This used to be the old mainline but
White is almost getting a better position by force here.} (8... Qe7 {This
doesn't make too much sense after} 9. Ne5 Nd7 10. Nxd7 Qxd7 (10... Bxd7 $6 11.
Bxd6 Qxd6 12. dxc5 Qxc5 $2 {This is losing on the spot. Otherwise, White would
have just enjoyed a healthy extra pawn.} 13. Bxh7+ Kxh7 14. Qh5+ Kg8 15. Ne4
$18) 11. dxc5 Bxc5 12. O-O {[%cal Ge3e4] with the idea to go e4 next,White is
at least slightly better here.}) ({With the knight on c6,} 8... Qc7 $6 {runs
into} 9. dxc5 $1 Bxg3 10. hxg3 e5 11. e4 $16 {with a huge advantage for White.}
) 9. e4 Be7 {This has always been considered as the thematic reaction to e3-e4.
} ({White gets a powerful initiative after} 9... dxe4 10. Nxe4 Nxe4 ({In the
event of} 10... Be7 11. dxc5 bxc5 12. Nxf6+ Bxf6 13. Qc2 g6 14. O-O-O $40 {
White gets huge attacking possibilities. The advance h2-h4-h5 is on the air.})
11. Bxe4 Bb7 12. Qa4 {An important tempo. White is freeing the d1-square for
the rook.} Rc8 13. dxc5 Bxc5 14. Rd1 Qe7 15. O-O Rfd8 (15... a5 16. Rfe1 Rfd8
17. Bh4 f6 18. Bd5 $18) 16. Rfe1 Rxd1 17. Rxd1 $16 {[%cal Gb2b4] Black does
not have a suitable way of stopping b2-b4.}) 10. e5 Nh5 11. Ng5 $1 {This
resource changed the evaluation of the entire vaiation.} Bxg5 12. Qxh5 g6 ({
Another illustrative line would be} 12... Bxd2+ 13. Kxd2 h6 14. Bh4 Ne7 15. Bf6
$1 $18 gxf6 16. Qxh6 f5 17. g4 {White is winning.}) 13. Qe2 cxd4 14. h4 Bh6 (
14... Bxd2+ 15. Qxd2 dxc3 16. bxc3 d4 17. c4 Qe7 18. Rb1 {White has a huge
attack here which was shown quite nicely in the model game by Jordan
Van-Foreest.}) 15. h5 dxc3 16. bxc3 Bg7 (16... Kg7 {This is just a mistake here
} 17. Nf3 Bb7 18. hxg6 hxg6 19. Rxh6 $1 Kxh6 20. Bh4 f6 21. exf6 Qc7 22. Qe3+
Kh7 23. Qg5 {White was completely winning here in the game of
Blohberger-Donchenko 2021}) 17. f4 Qc7 18. Nf3 d4 (18... Re8 {Black's idea is
to play ...Bf8 after h5-h6 but White's attack is just too fast.} 19. Rc1 Bb7
20. Ng5 $18 {[%cal Gg5h7,Gh5g6]}) 19. h6 Bh8 20. Rc1 $36 {Our idea is to
simply play against the bishop on h8} *

