{[%evp 0,21,27,27,30,30,54,57,54,36,44,26,35,39,24,36,58,25,23,33,32,28,54,59]
} 1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 {In this chapter, we are going to examine some sidelines
that Black might choose on move 2. At this point, I would like to make an
important clarification. Since the Slav setups can be subject of an entire
book, it will be impossible to cover them in the most extensive way. Therefore,
at this point, I will restrict myself from providing you with important
reference points. This knowledge will be enough to make you confident when
playing these positions in your games.} c6 (2... Bf5 {Whenever you see the
Black bishop being committed to f5 too early, always look for c2-c4 followed
by Qb3 at some point.} 3. c4 e6 4. Nc3 Nf6 ({Another important direction is} 
4... c6 5. Qb3 Qc7 {This move is slightly better than Qb6 because it allows
Black to keep a more compact pawn structure.} ({A typical reaction to} 5... Qb6
$6 {is} 6. c5 Qxb3 ({To completely different type of position leads} 6... Qc7
7. Bf4 Qc8 {when White should play} 8. Nh4 $14 {Going for the bishop pair is a
typical approach in Slav type of structures. Since the pawn structure is very
flexible, the potential power of White's bishop pair shouldn't be
underestimated.}) 7. axb3 {[%cal Gb3b4,Gb4b5] White's main idea in this type
of position is the advance b3-b4-b5. Therefore, Black usually plays} Nd7 ({
After} 7... Nf6 8. b4 a6 9. b5 $1 $16 {White enjoys a big advantage.}) 8. b4 {
White is ready to undermine Black's queenside structure by means of b4-b5.} a6
9. Bf4 Rc8 10. Nd2 $14 {[%cal Gd2b3,Gb3a5] Remember this typical idea. In this
structure, the knight is often heading for the a5-square. Defending the
b7-pawn is not an easy task for Black.}) 6. Bf4 dxc4 7. Bxc7 cxb3 {After the
queen exchange, White has complete control of the centre.} 8. e4 Bg6 9. axb3
Nf6 10. Nd2 Bb4 11. f3 $14 {White enjoys a lasting advantage.}) (4... Nc6 {
This move has been tried by Nepomniachtchi on several occasions. Black is
immediately putting pressure on d4. The drawback is that for the time being
the knight blocks the c7-pawn.  White's most natural way of developing the
pieces is} 5. Bf4 {[%cal Ge2e3,Ga1c1] planning to follow with natural moves
such as e2-e3 and Rc1.} Nf6 (5... Bb4 6. e3 Nf6 7. Rc1 {is just a
transposition.}) (5... Bd6 6. Bxd6 Qxd6 7. e3 Nf6 8. c5 Qe7 9. Bb5 O-O 10. Bxc6
bxc6 11. Ne5 $16) {A good exemplary line would be} 6. e3 Bb4 7. Rc1 {[%cal
Ga2a3] Black should play actively. Otherwise, White will follow with a2-a3
with a stable advantage.} Ne4 8. cxd5 exd5 9. Bd3 O-O 10. O-O $14 {In my
opinion, White retains better chances due to the misplaced c6-knight.}) 5. Nh4
{Not the most popular move but it feels quite easy to play for White after
this.} Bg6 (5... Bb4 6. Nxf5 exf5 7. Bg5 c5 {Otherwise the whole thing with
giving up the f5 bishop doesn't make a lot of sense.} ({Taking the pawn with} 
7... dxc4 {is risky -} 8. e3 b5 9. a4 $16 {It turns out that Black cannot keep
his queenside structure intact. A possible line would be} c6 10. axb5 cxb5 11.
Qf3 Qd5 12. Bxf6 Qxf3 13. gxf3 gxf6 14. Ke2 Bxc3 15. bxc3 $16 {[%cal Gf1h3,
Gh3f5] White has a huge advantage. His next move is going to be Bh3.}) 8. cxd5
Qa5 9. dxc5 Nxd5 10. Qxd5 Bxc3+ 11. Bd2 Bxd2+ 12. Qxd2 Qxd2+ (12... Qxc5 13.
Rc1) 13. Kxd2 Na6 14. Rc1 O-O-O+ 15. Ke1 Rd5 16. c6 {I don't believe Black has
full compensation for the pawn.}) 6. Qb3 Nc6 7. cxd5 exd5 8. e3 Bb4 (8... Rb8
9. Bd2 Bb4 10. O-O-O O-O 11. Nxg6 hxg6 12. f3 $40 {with the idea to go g4-h4
next}) 9. Bd2 (9. Nxg6 hxg6 10. Bd2 {This was played by Aronian but I believe
it's better to keep the option of Ng6 for later.} Qd6 {[%cal Gd6h2] Black can
now use this tempo compared to the mainline}) 9... Qe7 (9... Qd6 10. Be2) 10.
Be2 O-O 11. a3 Bxc3 12. Bxc3 Rab8 13. O-O $14 {White keeps a slight edge due
to his bishop pair and the possibility to put pressure along the c-file.}) (
2... Nc6 {Black wants to go for the Chigorin System but here we don't have to
hurry with the advance c2-c4.} 3. Bf4 Bg4 (3... Bf5 4. c4 e6 5. Nc3 {This is
covered under 2..Bf5}) 4. e3 e6 5. c4 Bd6 ({After} 5... Bb4+ 6. Nc3 Nf6 7. Rc1
O-O 8. Be2 $14 {White will go 0-0 next and the knight on c6 seems to be
misplaced. I won't go too much into the details but White is simply slightly
better here.}) 6. Bxd6 Qxd6 7. Nbd2 {White's next move is Qb3 to attack the
Black pawns on b7 and d5, and Rc1 with the idea to put more pressure on the
queenside. White has a small but lasting advantage.} Nge7 8. Qb3 $14) (2... e6
3. Bf4 Bd6 4. e3 Bxf4 5. exf4 Nf6 ({The alternative} 5... Ne7 {can be met by}
6. h4 $1 $146 {This has not been played before but you will see it's quite a
common plan in these positions.} b6 7. h5 h6 {Black must play this move to
stop the White pawn from going to h6 and weaken Black's kingside. However,
White now has a target to attack: the pawn on h6.} 8. g4 $40 {with the idea to
go g4-g5 next. White's kingside expansion is justified by the stable situation
in the centre.}) 6. Nbd2 O-O 7. c3 c5 {The most straightforward option.} ({
The alternative} 7... b6 {feels a little slow} 8. h4 {Once again, advancing the
h-pawn works very well for White.} c5 9. h5 h6 10. Ne5 $40 {White wants to
play Qf3-Bd3 next and launch an attack on the kingside}) 8. dxc5 {This is a
structural transformation that is favourable for White. In the near future,
White must transfer his d2-knight to d4. In such a case, the control of the
central squares e5 and d4 would provide White with good attacking chances on
the kingside.} Qc7 9. g3 Nbd7 10. Nb3 a5 ({After} 10... e5 11. Nxe5 Nxe5 12.
fxe5 Qxe5+ 13. Be2 Re8 14. Nd4 Bh3 15. f3 $14 {Besides his extra pawn, White
has a better structure.}) 11. Bg2 {This is a rare case where White wants the
bishop on g2 instead of d3, so that the knight on c5 does not hit the bishop.}
a4 12. Nbd4 Nxc5 13. O-O {I think White is slightly better here thanks to the
control on the dark squares.}) 3. Bf4 Qb6 {I played this myself in a corr.
game but it wasn't easy to defend even with the engine} (3... Bf5 4. e3 e6 5.
c4 {This is simply a better version of 3..Bf5 as here c6 has no use. White can
continue with Nc3-Qb3}) ({Of course, Black can try} 3... Nf6 4. e3 Bg4 {
when I think that} 5. Nbd2 {is the most precise option. White is going for the
bishop pair by means of h2-h3 followed by g2-g4.} e6 ({A very interesting line
might arise after} 5... Nbd7 6. h3 Bh5 7. g4 Bg6 8. g5 Ne4 9. h4 {White's
kingside space gives him serious initiative.} Nxd2 10. Qxd2 e6 11. O-O-O Be4
12. Rh3 $40 {[%cal Gh3g3,Gh4h5] White is ready to proceed with Rg3 followed
by h4-h5. Black has no obvious counterplay.}) ({The attempt to exchange the
f4-bishop with} 5... Nh5 {is well met by} 6. Bg5 h6 7. Bh4 g5 8. h3 $1 {
You should remember this typical idea. In many lines, the h5-knight will be
hanging.} Bf5 9. Ne5 Nf6 10. Bg3 $14 {Black has no enough compensation for the
weakened kingside.}) 6. h3 {This is the problem with putting the bishop on g4
as now White gets this important tempo and now Black has to part way with his
bishop one way or another.} Bxf3 7. Qxf3 Bd6 8. g4 Bxf4 9. Qxf4 Nbd7 10. O-O-O
$40 {[%cal Gh3h4,Gg4g5]}) 4. Qc1 Nf6 5. e3 Bf5 6. c4 {Again, we need this move
to fight for a space advantage.} Nbd7 7. Nc3 e6 8. h3 {This prophylactic move
secures the h2-square for the London bishop.} Ne4 (8... Be7 {This is what I
tried in the corr. game} 9. c5 Qd8 10. b4 Ne4 11. Nxe4 Bxe4 12. Nd2 $14) (8...
dxc4 {This move releases the tension but it wasn't easy for Black to play
after c5 as well.} 9. Nd2 Nd5 10. Nxc4 Qd8 11. Nd6+ Bxd6 12. Bxd6 $14) 9. c5
Qa5 10. a3 $1 Nxc3 11. b4 $14 {The point! We will take the knight on the next
move and we definitely have a slight edge here.} *

