attack.}) 7. Qf3 c6 8. Nd2 Bb7 9. O-O-O $40 {[%cal Gh2h4,Gf1d3] White is
clearly better due to his better development, space advantage and safer king.})
({If Black wants to play ...Nh5, it's better to start with} 4... Bb7 5. Bd3 Nh5
{Even in this case, however, White keeps a slight edge.} (5... Be7 {This would
transpose to the mainline}) 6. Bg5 Be7 7. Bxe7 Qxe7 8. O-O d5 {Black tries to
increase his central control. In this setup, however, the h5-knight is
misplaced.} ({An alternative would have been} 8... Nf6 9. c4 O-O 10. Nc3 d5 11.
cxd5 exd5 12. Rc1 $14 {This is a typical structure where Black has to play ...
c7-c5 at some point to create some counterplay but the downside is that the
hanging pawns will be vulnerable.}) 9. Ne5 Nf6 10. Nd2 O-O 11. a4 $1 {A very
subtle positional idea. Due to the threat of a4-a5, White wants to provoke the
advance ...a7-a5. In this scenario, the eventual ...c7-c5 will weaken both the
b5-square and the b6-pawn.} a5 {Otherwise a5 will be very hard to deal with.}
12. c3 Ba6 ({After} 12... Nbd7 13. f4 {[%cal Gf1f3,Gf3h3] with obtains a dream
version of the Stonewall structure. His ready to follow with Rf3-h3.}) 13. Bxa6
Nxa6 14. f4 c5 15. Rf3 Nd7 $6 16. Rh3 $40 {The central stability promises
White good attacking chances on the kingside.}) (4... c5 $6 {This is simply
bad in this move-order} 5. Nc3 {[%cal Gc3b5] Now, Black should reckon with the
