Stopping Nb5 with} 6... a6 {does not work in view of} 7. Qf3 $1 d5 {Now White
wins the exchange by force.} 8. Bxb8 Rxb8 9. Nc6 $16) 7. Ndb5 Nd5 8. Bd6 Bxc3+
9. bxc3 a6 10. Qxd5 $1 exd5 11. Nc7+ Qxc7 12. Bxc7 $14 {White has a stable
positional advantage.}) (5... Bb7 {This move prevents d4-d5 but not Nb5.} 6.
Nb5 Na6 (6... Nd5 7. Nd6+ Bxd6 8. Bxd6 $16) ({The move} 6... d6 {fails to} 7.
dxc5 $1) 7. Nd2 $1 {[%cal Gd2c4] The knight is heading to c4.} ({Premature
would have been} 7. Nd6+ {when after} Bxd6 8. Bxd6 Ne4 {Black is getting a
decent counterplay.}) {The other point behind 7.Nd2! is that after} 7... d5 {
White has the powerful} 8. g4 {Computer is very happy with this move!} Be7 9.
g5 {I can go further but I feel that White has achieved everything he was
dreaming of.}) 6. d5 $1 {The point of Nc3} Bb7 ({After} 6... d6 {the simplest
is} 7. dxe6 fxe6 8. e4 $1 {with the idea to go e4-e5 next.}) 7. e4 b5 8. Qe2 c4
9. g4 $1 {Immediately starting a kingside attack. Of course, White is planning
to castle long.} Bb4 10. g5 Nh5 11. Be3 O-O 12. O-O-O $16 {[%cal Gf1h3,Gh3g4]
White has a big advantage. He is planning the manoeuvre Bh3-g4.}) 5. h3 {
A useful prophylactic move. With the bishop already developed to e7, Black is
ready for ...Nh5.} O-O 6. Nbd2 c5 7. c3 cxd4 {This is the most annoying move
order.} ({After} 7... d5 8. Ne5 {we get a typical QGD setup where White has
