a strong centre. This is what Black is trying to avoid with the inclusion of ..
.cxd4.}) ({Another option is} 7... Bb7 8. Bd3 d6 9. O-O Nbd7 10. Qe2 {Now
White is ready for e3-e4 so that Black has to play cd-ed which would transpose
to the earlier cd4 line.}) 8. exd4 Ba6 {This is the point. Black usually
prefers to play this structure without light-squared bishops.} ({A very
popular setup is} 8... Bb7 9. Bd3 d6 10. O-O Nbd7 11. Bh2 a6 {Black is playing
in Hedgehog style. His main idea in this setup is to gradually prepare the
advance ...e6-e5. Typical preparatory moves are ...Qc7, ...Rfe8, and ...Bf8.
White's best idea is} 12. a4 {White is planning a4-a5 and then meet ...b6-b5
with c3-c4. In this way, White will create queenside targets.} Qc7 {The most
natural.} ({A similar idea is} 12... Re8 {Now, besides Qe2, I would like to
show an alternative plan -} 13. Ne1 {[%cal Ge1c2,Gc2b4] The knight is heading
to b4 or e3.} Bf8 ({In case of} 13... Nf8 14. Nc2 Ng6 {it's better to play} 15.
Ne3 {since Black has already indicated his intention to play on the kingside.}
e5 16. Re1 $14 {[%cal Gd1b3,Gd3f1,Gd2c4] Since the kingside is already
protected, White can start preparing his queenside play. His next move will be
Bf1 followed by Qb3 and Ndc4, targeting the b6-pawn as well as Black's centre.}
) 14. Nc2 g6 15. Re1 Qc7 16. Bf1 {The bishop always belongs to f1 in this
setup. It's very important to overprotect the g2-square.} Rac8 17. Nb4 Ra8 18.
Nc4 $14 {White's queenside pressure is quite annoying.}) 13. Qe2 Rfe8 {The
standard square for the rook.} ({If Black prefers to bring his rook to the
queenside with} 13... Rfc8 {White has another interesting plan at his disposal
-} 14. Rfe1 Bf8 15. Nf1 Qb8 16. Ne3 $14 {[%cal Gf3d2,Gf2f3,Gd2e4] White's idea
is to establish a central superiority by means of Nd2 followed by f2-f3 and
Ne4.}) 14. a5 b5 15. c4 bxc4 16. Nxc4 {This idea works very well when the
Black queen has already occupied the c7-square. Now, Black should spend a
tempo on} Qb8 {when after} 17. Nfd2 Bf8 {a very strong move would be} 18. Rab1
{[%cal Gb2b4,Gb4b5] preparing the advance of the b-pawn. A possible follow-up
would be} e5 19. dxe5 dxe5 20. Rfd1 $14 {[%cal Gb2b4,Gb4b5] with an advantage
for White.}) 9. Bxa6 Nxa6 10. O-O Qc8 11. a4 Qb7 12. Ne5 Nc7 {[%cal Gc7d5,
Ga7a6,Gb6b5] Black's idea in this setup is ...Ncd5 followed by ...a7-a6 and ...
b6-b5, thus starting a minority attack on the queenside.} 13. Re1 Ncd5 ({
In case of} 13... a6 14. c4 $1 b5 (14... Bb4 15. Nd3) 15. b3 $1 $14 {[%cal
Ge5d3,Gf4g5] The c7-knight feels a bit misplaced. Having good central control,
White can already consider organizing a kingside attack.}) 14. Bh2 a6 15. g4 h6
16. h4 $40 {I believe in White's attacking potential on the kingside.} *

