{[%evp 0,33,27,32,21,14,47,47,44,49,80,29,52,12,36,36,42,35,47,41,42,24,65,83,
115,100,87,80,76,72,65,55,62,39,40,47]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 g6 3. Nc3 {This is my
preferred way of fighting against the ...g7-g6 setup. Recently, this
continuation is known as Jobava Attack. White is preparing the advance e2-e4.
At the same time, he is ready to answer ...d7-d5 with Nb5. In this chapter, we
shall take a look at the Pirc setup.} Bg7 {This is the traditional move.} ({
The alternative is} 3... d6 {Black plays this to delay the development of the
f8 bishop. The idea is that when White plays Qd2 followed by Bh6, Black will
take on h6 in one go.} 4. e4 c6 {The most flexible choice. Black opens the way
of his queen and makes possible the advance ...b7-b5.} ({Preparing ...c7-c5 is
hardly a good strategy here. Let's take a look at an example -} 4... Nbd7 5.
Nf3 Bg7 6. Qd2 c5 $6 ({After} 6... O-O 7. Bh6 e5 8. h4 $40 {I don't see a
particular difference for Black with or without ...c7-c6. White enjoys a
strong attack.}) 7. dxc5 {Simple and strong} Nxc5 ({The alternative} 7... e5 {
weakens the d5 square and now we don't really have to play for mate} 8. Bh6
Bxh6 9. Qxh6 Nxc5 ({After} 9... dxc5 10. O-O-O {Black's position is completely
cramped.}) 10. O-O-O Qe7 {Otherwise Ne5 is hard to parry} 11. Bb5+ Bd7 12.
Bxd7+ Ncxd7 (12... Kxd7 13. Nb5 $18) 13. Nb5 $18 {White is already winning.})
8. e5 {Having more active pieces, White immediately opens the position.} Nh5 ({
Another possibility is} 8... Nfe4 {when after} 9. Nxe4 Nxe4 10. Qb4 {White
develops a strong initiative.} d5 11. Bb5+ Bd7 12. Rd1 e6 (12... a6 13. Bd3 $14
{[%cal Ge1g1,Gf3d4]}) 13. c4 Bc6 14. Nd4 {White has an overwhelming advantage
here.}) 9. Be3 O-O 10. h3 {[%cal Gg2g4] The advance g2-g4 is a huge threat now
and it's not easy to parry that. I believe White is simply winning here.}) 5.
Qd2 b5 {Besides gaining queenside space, Black indirectly attacks the e4-pawn
in view of the idea ...b5-b4.} ({The main alternative is} 5... Nbd7 6. Nf3 Bg7
{Some players develop the bishop on g7 when the White knight appears on f3,
The reason is that White has no longer the Saemisch setup based on f2-f3 and
g2-g4. Nevertheless, White still has a strong attack.} ({An important line is} 
6... Qa5 {Black's idea is to go ...e7-e5 next. Therefore, White's thematic
reaction is} 7. e5 $1 dxe5 8. dxe5 Ng4 ({if} 8... Nh5 9. Be3 Ng7 10. O-O-O Ne6
11. Bc4 {I don't want to go really deep here as the position itself looks lost
for Black plus the engine gives an overwhelming advantage to White.}) ({
The endgame arising after} 8... Nd5 9. Nxd5 Qxd5 10. Qxd5 cxd5 {is not easy
for Black. White should play} 11. h4 {[%cal Gh4h5,Gh5h6]} h5 {Otherwise after
h5-h6 Black will have no space} 12. O-O-O e6 13. Bb5 a6 14. Bxd7+ Bxd7 15. Bg5
{with Bf6 coming next. White is just much better here.}) {The thematic} 9. e6
$146 {is very promising as Black is underdeveloped:} ({A GM game saw} 9. Ne4 $5
Qxd2+ 10. Nexd2 Bg7 11. Nc4 b5 12. h3 Nxf2 13. Kxf2 bxc4 14. Bxc4 Nb6 15. Bb3
$14 {White’s position is more pleasant, and Black's attempt at harassing the
b3-bishop simply lost a pawn.} c5 $6 16. Be3 $1 c4 17. Bxb6 cxb3 18. axb3 $16 {
This was Hamdouchi – Marin, Sitges 1999. White is just a pawn up.}) 9... fxe6
10. h3 Ngf6 11. Bc4 Nd5 12. O-O $40 {Nd5-Nc7 is a big threat now} Nxf4 (12...
Nxc3 13. Bxe6 $1 $18) 13. Qxf4 {I can't see Black surviving this for more than
5 moves.}) 7. Bh6 O-O (7... Bxh6 8. Qxh6) 8. h4 {This is move you play when
you want to checkmate your opponent.} ({A solid alternative is} 8. e5 {This is
a move you play if you want to play for two results.} dxe5 ({After} 8... Nd5 9.
Nxd5 cxd5 10. h4 $36 {White enjoys an overwhelming attack.}) 9. Bxg7 Kxg7 10.
dxe5 Ng4 11. O-O-O Qb6 12. e6 $1 Ndf6 (12... fxe6 13. h3 Nxf2 (13... Nge5 14.
Ng5 Nf6 15. Na4 $18 {[%cal Ga4c5]}) 14. Na4 {wins a piece}) 13. exf7 Qxf2 14.
Bc4 b5 15. Bb3 Qxd2+ 16. Rxd2 a6 17. Re1 c5 18. Be6 Bxe6 19. Rxe6 Kxf7 20. Rde2
{We will pick up the e7-pawn and I believe White is slightly better here
without any risk.}) 8... Bxh6 ({The typical reaction to} 8... e5 {is} 9. h5 {
when the following sequence is possible} Nxh5 10. O-O-O Re8 11. dxe5 dxe5 12.
g4 Nf4 13. Bxg7 Kxg7 14. Nxe5 {White forces the transition into a slightly
better endgame.} Rxe5 15. Qxf4 Qg5 16. Qxg5 Rxg5 17. Be2 $14 {[%cal Gf2f4,
Ge4e5] Here because the pawn is still on b7 Black cannot play b4 and thus he
cannot stop our pawn march in the centre}) 9. Qxh6 Ng4 10. Qd2 h5 11. Ng5 $40 {
[%cal Gf1e2,Ge1c1,Gg2g4] White's kingside attack is pretty straightforward.
After casting long, White will proceed with Be2 followed by f2-f3 and g2-g4.})
6. Bd3 {Usually we meet b5 with Bd3 so that our knight can come back to e2 if
Black goes b4} Nbd7 7. Nf3 Bg7 8. Bh6 O-O {As we have already seen, even after
playing Nf3 White can still organize a kingside attack.} ({The alternative is} 
8... Bxh6 9. Qxh6 e5 (9... b4 10. Ne2 Qa5 11. O-O {This would eventually
transpose as Black's only logical plan is to play Ba6}) 10. h3 Qe7 {with the
idea to go Qf8} 11. O-O Bb7 12. a4 {Remember this thematic idea. White wants
to use Black's overextended queenside.} b4 13. Ne2 c5 ({Another instructive
line is} 13... Qf8 14. Qd2 a5 15. c3 $1 {Quite typically for this line, Whtie
starts playing on both wings. The game might continue} bxc3 16. bxc3 Qe7 {
[%cal Ge8g8]} 17. Rab1 Bc8 18. Ng3 {White is simply better on both sides of
the board}) 14. dxe5 dxe5 ({Taking with the knight} 14... Nxe5 {does not work
in view of} 15. Nxe5 dxe5 16. Bb5+ {when Black is in trouble.}) 15. Ng3 Qf8 16.
Qe3 Qe7 17. Rfd1 O-O 18. Qg5 $16 {[%cal Gd3b5,Gg3f5,Gg5e7] Black has too many
weaknesses. He faces big difficulties handling White's multiple threats.}) 9.
Bxg7 (9. h4 {This is possible as well but Black can probably defend with
precise play} e5 {Black should immediately strike in the centre.} ({After} 9...
Bxh6 10. Qxh6 {White usually gets decent attacking chances.} Ng4 11. Qd2 h5 ({
After} 11... Ndf6 {White's typical reaction is} 12. h5 Nxh5 13. Nh2 Nxh2 14.
Rxh2 $40 {with a strong attack.}) 12. Ng5 e5 13. Be2 $40 {[%cal Gf2f3,Gg2g4]
Defending the d4 pawn and putting pressure on the g4-knight with the intention
to go f3-g4 later on.}) 10. Bxg7 Kxg7 11. h5 {This move marks the beginning of
a sequence that is pretty much forced -} (11. O-O-O $6 h5 {It's not very easy
to breach Black's kingside now}) 11... Nxh5 12. O-O-O Re8 13. g4 Nf4 14. dxe5
dxe5 15. Nxe5 Rxe5 16. Qxf4 Qg5 17. Qxg5 Rxg5 18. Be2 b4 $1 {Thanks to the
pawn on b5, Black has this important resource which sort of saves the day for
him.}) 9... Kxg7 10. a4 {Once again, we employ this thematic break.} b4 11. Ne2
a5 12. Ng3 $40 {The advance h2-h4-h5 followed by Qg5 is a huge threat now.
Additionally, White can always switch to queenside play with c2-c3.}) 4. e4 d6
(4... d5 $6 {This is simply bad to mix Gruenfeld and Pirc together} 5. Nb5 Na6
6. e5 Nd7 7. Nc3 c6 8. Bxa6 bxa6 9. Nf3 $14 {Black's counterplay on the
queenside is ruined because of the structure and White can simply continue
with Qd2-Bh6 and even 0-0.}) 5. Qd2 c6 ({In the line} 5... O-O 6. Bh6 {White
usually manages to develop a dangerous attack. At this point, Black has many
options but none of them solves the problems.} e5 ({The structure arising after
} 6... c5 7. d5 {is also difficult for Black. After the exchange of the
dark-squared bishops, White just starts pushing his kingside pawns.} Nbd7 ({
Nothing changes} 7... a6 8. h4 b5 9. Bxg7 Kxg7 10. h5 {Black's king is too
vulnerable in these positions.} Nbd7 ({Taking the e4-pawn with} 10... b4 11.
Nce2 $1 Nxe4 {backfires after} 12. Qe3 Nf6 13. hxg6 fxg6 14. Nf4 {[%cal Ge1c1,
Gg1h3,Gh3g5] White is completely winning here}) 11. hxg6 fxg6 12. Nf3 Kg8 {
Sidestepping Qh6 checks} 13. Ng5 {[%cal Gg5e6]} Ne5 14. Be2 $16 {[%cal Gf2f4]
with f2-f4 to follow. White has an obvious advantage.}) ({A bit more reliable
but passive is} 7... Bxh6 8. Qxh6 Nbd7 9. Nf3 {[%cal Gf3g5]} Ng4 10. Qh4 Ngf6
11. Be2 a6 12. a4 $14 {Black does not have counterplay. White is better due to
his big space advantage.}) 8. Bxg7 ({But not} 8. h4 Bxh6 9. Qxh6 Ne5 {when
Black gets some counterplay.}) 8... Kxg7 9. f3 Qa5 10. g4 Rb8 11. a4 a6 12.
Nge2 b5 13. Ng3 $40 {[%cal Gh2h4,Gh4h5] Black's play on the queenside has
stopped whereas our attack on the kingside won't be easily repelled. Note that
after b4 we will go Nd1-e3-c4.}) (6... c6 7. h4 {With the idea to go h5. Black
would eventually have to go for e5 break which would lead to the mainline.}) (
6... Nbd7 {This is possible but it makes more sense to put the knight to c6 as
Black would have to break White's centre with either e5 or c5 and in those
scenarios, the knight does a much better job on c6.} 7. h4 e5 8. Bxg7 Kxg7 9. h5
Nxh5 10. Be2 Ndf6 ({White is winning on the spot after} 10... Nhf6 $2 11. Qh6+
Kg8 12. dxe5 Nxe5 13. O-O-O $18 {[%cal Gg2g4,Gg4g5] with g2-g4-g5 to follow.})
11. O-O-O Qe7 12. Bxh5 Nxh5 13. Nd5 Qd8 14. Ne2 $40 {White has a dangerous
attack.}) 7. Bxg7 Kxg7 8. f3 Nc6 9. Nge2 {This is supposed to be the dream KID/
Saemisch variation for White. Our idea is simple 0-0-0 and roll the pawns on
the kingside.}) (5... Nbd7 6. Nf3 {is just a transposition.}) ({Another
important direction is} 5... Nc6 6. O-O-O O-O 7. f3 {I feel this is more
precise as Black cannot play e5 just yet.} ({After} 7. Nf3 Bg4 {Black starts
putting pressure on d4.}) ({An instructive line is} 7. Bh6 e5 8. Bxg7 Kxg7 9.
Nge2 Ng4 $1 10. Qe1 Qh4 $1 {Cominbed with Ng4 and Qf6 this is the way for
Black but not at all easy to find as it hasn't been played till now. In my
opinion, a logical follow-up would be} 11. g3 Qf6 12. f4 Ne3 13. dxe5 dxe5 14.
Nd5 Nxd5 15. exd5 Ne7 16. fxe5 Qxe5 17. Nf4 Qxe1 18. Rxe1 {White is of course
a bit better but maybe Black can hold this endgame.}) 7... a6 8. Bh6 e5 9. Nge2
$40 {Now Black doesn't have Ng4 ideas and I think our attack on the kingside
will be way faster than Black's.}) ({After} 5... c5 6. dxc5 dxc5 7. Qxd8+ Kxd8
8. O-O-O+ {White has tremendous initiative.}) 6. Bh6 Bxh6 7. Qxh6 Qa5 8. Bd3 c5
{The most played move although I feel White is still much better here} ({
Another principled approach is} 8... b5 9. Nf3 b4 10. Ne2 Ba6 {Nevertheless,
exchanging the bishops does not solve the issues in Black's position.} 11. O-O
Bxd3 12. cxd3 Nbd7 (12... Qh5 13. Qd2 Qb5 14. e5 $1 $40) 13. Rfe1 {Asking
Black to commit} Qh5 14. Qd2 Qb5 15. Ng3 O-O {Otherwise White would play Qh6
again.} 16. e5 {White has winning attack here}) (8... Nbd7 9. Nf3 Qh5 10. Qd2
Qa5 11. O-O O-O {Black doesn't have any other useful moves as after e5 we
would go back to Qh6 and Black can't castle again. The last move, however, has
a drawback -} 12. Nd5 $1 Qd8 {Forced} 13. Nxf6+ exf6 (13... Nxf6 14. e5 Ne8 15.
Qh6 {White has a decisive attack here.}) 14. h4 $40 {with an obvious
advantage.}) 9. d5 Nbd7 10. Nf3 c4 (10... b5 11. Bxb5 Rb8 12. Bxd7+ Bxd7 13.
O-O Rxb2 {Till here it was played in the game MVL vs Dominguez.} 14. Nd1 {
This was missed by MVL} Rb4 15. e5 dxe5 16. c3 Rb7 17. Ne3 {White is simply
crashing through here.}) 11. Bxc4 Qc5 12. Bd3 Qxf2+ 13. Kxf2 Ng4+ 14. Ke2 Nxh6
{Till now it was quite forced} 15. h3 $1 {Strong move cutting the knight off
the board} O-O 16. Kd2 a6 17. b4 $14 {With the simple idea of Na4-c4-c5 and if
Black tries to stop it we have a juicy square for the knight on c6.} *

