{[%evp 0,38,24,18,27,-7,40,40,40,44,30,-10,-10,-5,1,1,-7,-24,16,12,12,13,14,7,
3,6,6,0,13,0,12,12,13,-2,-21,-21,0,0,-3,-4,-4]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 g6 3. Nc3 d5
4. Nf3 Bg7 {Probably the best move in the position. Besides this and 4...c6,
all other moves lead to an advantage for White.} (4... a6 {This is possible
although none of the top players goes for it for an obvious reason as it's slow
against White's initiative on the kingside.} 5. Qd2 {with the idea to play Bh6
and 0-0-0} Bg7 6. O-O-O O-O 7. h4 $1 h5 {Otherwise h5 would have been terrible
for Black.} 8. Ng5 b5 9. f3 Nbd7 10. e4 $40) (4... Nh5 {This move does not
make much sense here but still we must know how to react against it.} 5. Be5 $1
{Provoking f6} f6 6. Bg3 Nxg3 7. hxg3 f5 {Otherwise, it's difficult to do
anything with the dark-squared bishop.} 8. e3 Bg7 9. Ne2 {With the idea to go
Nf4,Be2/d3,0-0 and open up the centre with c4. It feels like a very good
version of Stonewall.}) (4... c5 $6 {Black is not ready for this move. White
can simply capture the pawn and hang on to it.} 5. dxc5 Qa5 (5... Bg7 6. e4 $1
Qa5 {Black must try to create counterplay by pinning the White knight.} 7. exd5
Ne4 8. Be5 {It is important to exchange the dark-squared bishops.} Bxe5 9. Nxe5
Nxc3 10. Qd2 $1 {With the idea to get back the piece. White is simply much
better here.}) (5... Nc6 6. e4 $1 {If you can you should always attack the
centre.} Nxe4 7. Nxe4 dxe4 8. Qxd8+ Nxd8 (8... Kxd8 9. Ng5) 9. Ne5 $1 {Bb5
check is big threat now} a6 {What else?} 10. Nc4 $16 {[%cal Gc4b6] I don't see
how Back can stop Nb6 thus giving White a clear advantage.}) 6. Nd4 {[%cal
Gd4b3]} Qxc5 7. Be5 $16 {[%csl Yd5] White wins the d5-pawn with a large
advantage.}) (4... c6 5. h3 {It's important to play this to have a cover for
the bishop on f4.} Bg7 6. e3 O-O 7. Be2 {Our plan is simple. We want to castle
next and play normal chess. Black has now few options here} Nbd7 {This is the
most flexible move for Black.} (7... b6 {This has been played a few times, but
it doesn't solve Black's problems.} 8. O-O Bb7 9. a4 {We want to get a5 next.}
a5 {This is the only way to prevent White's idea.} 10. Re1 {[%cal Ge3e4]} Nbd7
11. Bd3 $14 {With e4 coming next and White has a slight edge here.}) (7... b5 {
This in a way stops a4 but weakens c5-square.} 8. O-O Nbd7 9. a3 a5 10. Bd3 Bb7
11. b4 $14 {We have stopped b4 and are now ready to play Re1 and e3-e4.}) (7...
Bf5 8. O-O a5 (8... Nbd7 $6 9. g4 {White takes advantage of Black's last move
to chase the unstable bishop.} Be6 10. Ng5 Ne8 11. Bg3 $14 {With the idea to
play f4 next.}) 9. Bd3 Bxd3 10. cxd3 $1 $40 {Black doesn't have any
counterplay against e4-e5}) 8. O-O Re8 {Although this has been played many
times, it's almost impossible to get ...e7-e5 for Black.} 9. Bh2 {Asking Black
what does he want next.} a5 10. a4 Nb6 {This was played in one of the games
but I don't see what Black wants after b3} (10... Ne4 $6 11. Nxe4 dxe4 12. Nd2
Nf6 13. c3 $16 {[%cal Gd1c2,Gd2c4,Gb2b4]}) 11. b3 $14) 5. Nb5 {White is
forcing Black to put his knight on the rim.} Na6 6. e3 O-O (6... Nh5 {This has
been played recently by Aronian and Mamedyarov.} 7. Bg5 c6 8. Nc3 Nc7 9. h3 {
White wants to play g4 at some point to push the Black knight back in case of
necessity.} O-O 10. Bh4 {This is a prophylactic move against ...h6 or ...f6.}
b6 11. Be2 Bb7 12. O-O c5 13. a4 Ne6 14. a5 {With the ideas of a6-Ne5 in the
air. I feel White is slightly better here.}) (6... c6 7. Nc3 Nc7 (7... Nb8 8.
h3 {is just a transposition.}) (7... O-O {This is simply bad.} 8. Bxa6 bxa6 9.
Ne5 $14) 8. h3 {It's important not to let Black bishop on g4.} O-O 9. Bd3 {
tranposes.}) 7. h3 Ne4 {Another move which I employed myself. The idea here is
to not let White knight go on c3} (7... Bf5 {This is sort of a semi-waiting
move which I employed myself but if we know what to do then it shouldn't be a
big deal.} 8. Bd3 {This was played by Blubaum who is sort of an expert in this
line.} (8. c3 c6 9. Na3 Qb6 (9... Nc7 10. Be2 $14 {[%cal Ge1g1,Gc3c4]}) 10. Qb3
Nd7 11. Be2 e5 {This is not been played before but it seems to give Black
decent chances for equality} 12. Nxe5 Nxe5 13. Bxe5 Bxe5 14. Qxb6 axb6 15. Bxa6
Bd6 16. Bxb7 Bxa3 17. bxa3 Ra5 18. c4 dxc4 19. Bxc6 Rc8 20. d5 Rxa3 $11) 8...
Bxd3 9. cxd3 c5 10. O-O cxd4 11. Nbxd4 Nd7 12. Bg3 {We have a slightly better
position with the idea of Rb1 followed by b4 next.} Re8 13. Rb1 e5 14. Nb5 Qb6
15. Nc3 d4 {Otherwise it's not so easy to defend this pawn.} 16. exd4 exd4 17.
Ne4 $14) (7... c5 8. c3 Bd7 9. a4 c4 10. Nd2 {This move prevents ...Ne4 and
prepares for e4 or b3.} Bxb5 11. axb5 Nc7 12. e4 $1 dxe4 (12... e6 13. e5 Nd7
14. g3 Nxb5 15. h4 $44 {[%cal Gh4h5,Gd1g4]}) 13. Bxc4 {With pair of bishops
White's position is slightly preferable.}) (7... c6 8. Nc3 Nc7 (8... b6 9. Be2
Bb7 10. O-O Nc7 11. a4 {with the idea to go a5 next.} a5 12. Nb1 {With the
idea to go Na3/d2 and c4. If Black goes for c5, b5 will always be a weak
square.}) (8... c5 {This is simply bad} 9. Bxa6 bxa6 10. Be5 cxd4 11. Qxd4 $14)
(8... Qb6 {[%csl Rb2]} 9. Rb1 c5 {This has been the choice of Rajdabov and
Adhiban} (9... Bf5 {A natural move as Black wants to play ...Ne4 or ...Nb4} 10.
Bd3 Bxd3 11. cxd3 {We see this typical recapture again. I will stress that
White should not be afraid of the double d-pawns, as we can aim for a pawn
attack on the queenside with b2-b4-b5, or play in the centre with e3-e4.} c5 {
If Black does not play this move, he is just worse with a passive position.}
12. Be5 {White needs the London bishop here to counter Black's potential
pressure on the long diagonal..} e6 13. O-O Rfc8 {It is natural for Black to
bring a rook to the c-file.} 14. Na4 Qd8 15. Nxc5 Nxc5 16. dxc5 Rxc5 17. Qa4 {
The position is objectively equal, but White retains some practical chances
thanks to our better placed minor pieces. Black's queenside is also slightly
vulnerable.}) 10. Be5 cxd4 (10... Rd8 11. Bxa6 bxa6 12. O-O $14) 11. Bxd4 Qd8
12. Bxa6 bxa6 13. O-O $14 {Thanks to the pawn structure, White seems to be
slightly better here.}) 9. Bd3 {With bishop on d3, we can later play for e4} b6
(9... Nce8 {Black takes time to relocate this knight to d6, where it has good
control over the centre. The drawback is that it will be almost impossible for
Black to play ...e5.} 10. O-O Nd6 11. a4 a5 12. Re1 Re8 (12... Bf5 $6 13. Bxf5
Nxf5 14. e4) 13. Be5 $14 {With the idea of eventually getting Nd2 and e4 or we
can also play Ne2-b3-c4}) 10. O-O Bb7 11. a4 {Once again, we see this thematic
idea.} a5 {This move stops the White pawn from advancing but weakens the
b5-square.} (11... c5 12. a5 {I don't want to go too much into the detail here
but practically I feel White is slightly better as we have more space on the
queenside plus Black can never challenge the control over the e5-square.}) 12.
Re1 $14 {White is ready to open the centre with e4.}) 8. Nd2 c6 (8... Nxd2 9.
Qxd2 c6 10. Nc3 Nc7 11. O-O-O $1 {Surprise!} Ne6 12. Be5 Bxe5 13. dxe5 b5 14.
h4 $40 {The objective evaluation should be okay for Black but in a practical
game it's always easier to play this as White.}) 9. Nxe4 dxe4 (9... cxb5 10.
Nd2 b4 11. Bd3 $16) 10. Nc3 c5 {This is the only way to justify Black's 8th
move.} 11. Nxe4 {Finally we have a position which has never been played before}
(11. Bxa6 bxa6 12. O-O cxd4 13. exd4 Bxd4 14. Bh6 Re8 15. Qe1 Bb7 16. Rd1 e5
17. Nxe4 Qh4 18. Nd6 Qxh6 19. Nxb7 Bxb2 $132) 11... cxd4 12. exd4 Qd5 $1 (12...
Bxd4 13. c3 Nc5 14. Nxc5 Bxc5 15. Bc4 {With the idea to play Qe2,0-0 next. I
believe White is slightly better here.}) 13. Nc3 Qf5 {Another precise move} (
13... Qxd4 $6 14. Qxd4 Bxd4 15. Nd5 {Computer gives White a clear advantage and
I am not going to argue on that :)}) 14. Be3 Nb4 {Another only move} 15. Rc1
Rd8 16. Bc4 Nc6 17. Ne2 Nxd4 18. Nxd4 Bxd4 19. O-O Qe4 $11 {After making
almost 7-8 only moves, Black has finally equalised here but this has happened
only because I was analysing with the engine. In a practical game, Black's
play is very difficult.} *

